<div id="p1098" class="blockpost rowodd firstpost">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#1&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=1098#p1098">2010-03-08 01:44:05</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=90800">nasa42</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3>BEP-RFC.  Verifying the author of a .torrent file (verified torrents).</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>Hi,<br />Here, I'm proposing a specification which basically integrates OpenPGP with BitTorrent and which can be used to sign and verify a given .torrent metadata file.<br /><br /><strong>PROPOSAL:</strong><br /><br />The &quot;info&quot; section of a .torrent file may contain the fingerprint of author/uploader's OpenPGP key. This key is usually 20 bytes in length. (The fingerprint is from now on referred as &quot;author_key&quot;).<br />If &quot;author_key&quot; is present in &quot;info&quot; section, the .torrent file MUST contain a field called &quot;encrypted_info_hash&quot;.<br />This field contains the value of &quot;info hash&quot; encrypted by Private Key of the author.<br />Note that &quot;encrypted_info_hash&quot; is outside the &quot;info section&quot; and hence does not affect the &quot;info hash&quot; (avoiding a circular-dependency).<br /><br />Users (or user's software) or indexing/searching web-services may verify that the torrent is truly signed by the claiming author by looking up the fingerprint on any OpenPGP keyserver (Ex: pgp.mit.edu, keyserver.ubuntu.com:11371 etc.), getting the public key, decrypting &quot;encrypted_info_hash&quot; and comparing it for equality against .torrent's &quot;info_hash&quot;.<br /><br /><strong>BENEFITS:</strong><br /> <br />1. Users can verify that given .torrent file generates from the author it claims to be.<br />2. Users can verify that two .torrent files generate from the same author.<br />&nbsp; 2a. Users can choose to download the .torrent file only from an trusted author. (They may have downloaded .torrent files from the same author in past to gain trust. And now can verify the fact that this new .torrent file comes from the same trusted author).<br />&nbsp; 2b. If an author releases a new version of her product, users can verify that the author of the torrent of new version is same as of old one.<br />3. Partially solves the problem of <a href="http://forum.bittorrent.org/viewtopic.php?id=152" rel="nofollow">http://forum.bittorrent.org/viewtopic.php?id=152</a><br />4. In a distributed environment where indexing, searching and hosting of BitTorrent metadata files are being separated, verification and trust can play a key role.<br />5. Web-of-trust feature of PKI can assist users in choosing a better/safe/official torrent.<br /><br /><strong>DISADVANTAGES: </strong><br /><br />1. May not be compatible with current version of BitTorrent protocol. [UPDATE (3 days later): I was wrong, it is compatible. (Originally thought that can not modify the &quot;info&quot; section).]<br />2. Will enlarge the .torrent metadata file by a few bytes. (20+128 bytes for 1024-bit RSA, 20+256 for 2048-bit RSA Private Key, given the &quot;info hash&quot; is 20 bytes in size irrespective of the fact whether it is encrypted from its binary form or from its hex-string form).<br /><br /><strong>NOTES: </strong><br />1. This BEP does not intend to verify the author of the _content_ being shared, but rather the fact <br />that author of two .torrent metadata files is same.<br /><br /><strong>EXAMPLE: </strong><br />1. If Ubuntu signs its torrents, we can now guarantee that given .torrent file originates from Ubuntu and is genuine.<br />2. People can browse torrents by a particular author by visiting URLs like <a href="http://www.torrentz.eu/authors/c5986b4f1257ffa86632cba746181433fbb75451" rel="nofollow">http://www.torrentz.eu/authors/c5986b4f &hellip; 33fbb75451</a> (just an example, link doesn't exist).<br /><br />I'm ready to write a standardised BEP document, if I get enough +1s.<br /><br /><strong>LICENCE:</strong> I hereby declare to put the above proposal/document in public domain.<br />Vikrant Chaudhary<br /><a href="http://vikrant.co.in/" rel="nofollow">http://vikrant.co.in/</a><br /><br /><strong>UPDATE</strong> 23-March-2010 - Corrected 20+64 to 20+128 and 20+128 to 20+256.</p>
					<p class="postedit"><em>Last edited by nasa42 (2010-03-22 21:28:11)</em></p>
				</div>
				<div class="postsignature"><hr />-- Vikrant Chaudhary<br /><a href="http://vikrant.co.in/" rel="nofollow">http://vikrant.co.in/</a></div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
