<div id="p1156" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#9&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=1156#p1156">2010-03-19 19:04:55</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=90770">mjfrancis</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: BEP-RFC.  Verifying the author of a .torrent file (verified torrents).</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>The problem, in turn, with only having a signature outside the Info is that it precludes specifying a unique author for a given torrent. While this would make some sense for the case you describe, it would make the problem of clients communicating not just the question &quot;What is any old signature&quot;, but &quot;What is the signature I can verify against some external trust model&quot; a lot harder.<br /><br />Assuming a model in which a signature is embedded inside the Info (which is not the only model to achieve the above goal - a suitable specified key fingerprint would also do the job, but would leave you to exchange the actual unique signature separately as metadata), a DSA signature is a lot smaller than RSA, and both of those give you the option of plugging in to an existing PK trust relationship via an x.509 certificate chain or OpenPGP trust web.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
