<div id="p1160" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#11&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=1160#p1160">2010-03-20 18:14:52</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=90770">mjfrancis</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: BEP-RFC.  Verifying the author of a .torrent file (verified torrents).</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>I think we're talking at cross purposes again a little. The point I was trying to get across was that without one of either a signature or a key fingerprint inside the Info, you can't fulfill the requirement of being able to specify a unique author, and that actually performing the verification becomes much trickier. Let me illustrate.<br /><br />Assumptions: There is a torrent we expect to have been created by a known entity (possibly one out of several) and signed by their key. We have a magnet link.<br /><br />Model 1. Fingerprint inside Info<br /><br />1. Peer A bootstraps from the magnet link and finds peer B<br />2. Peer A gets the Info from peer B through metadata and verifies against the hash. On failure, dispose of peer B<br />3. Peer A retrieves the correct key from the known fingerprint in the Info, either through metadata from peer B, by already having it, or by downloading it through other means (keyserver). If retrieved through metadata and non-matching, dispose of peer B<br />4. Peer A gets the one and only signature from peer B through metadata and verifies (key, signature, info hash). On failure, dispose of peer B<br />5. Peer A verifies the key by whatever external means are appropriate (public key embedded in client, x.509 certificate chain, OpenPGP trust web, ...). On failure, there is nothing wrong with peer B - but this is not the torrent we are looking for<br />6. Verification is complete<br /><br />Model 2. Fingerprint outside Info<br /><br />1. Peer A bootstraps from the magnet link and finds peer B<br />2. Peer A gets the Info from peer B through metadata and verifies against the hash. On failure, dispose of peer B<br />3. Peer A asks peer B for a fingerprint. Peer B gives peer A some fingerprint; the fingerprint cannot be verified as being the author's<br />4. Peer A searches for a key matching the unverified fingerprint as above.<br />5. Peer A gets an unverified signature from peer B through metadata and verifies (key, signature, info hash). On failure... what? There may be more than one key and signature<br />6. Peer A verifies the key as above. On failure... what? We may not have got the right key,signature pair. We may have found a valid key for an unknown actor (not useful). Etc etc.<br /><br /><br />In the first model, the fingerprint being part of Info guarantees that the decision on what to do next is obvious at each step. In the second, the only remedy for the failure of one of the steps is &quot;repeat until false&quot; - hoping that eventually the right combination will be achieved in a random search of peers.<br /><br />Additionally, with regard to a detail I glossed over above - in practical terms, the metadata is as likely to be downloaded from multiple peers as just one. In model one, there is only supposed to be one possible version of each metadata item, so assuming a set containing both valid and attack peers, the standard response of &quot;on failure, put peers that contributed to the failure on solo request allocation and retry&quot; is sufficient for each individual item. In model two this is clearly not going to work - remote peers may not even be talking about the same content in the first place.<br /><br /><br />Model one is essentially what I'm currently implementing in Bobbin. Some time in the not too distant future I'll have some more code to point at for purposes of demonstration.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

