<div id="p1216" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#23&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=1216#p1216">2010-03-26 12:09:12</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89618">The 8472</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Azureus Developer</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: BEP-RFC.  Verifying the author of a .torrent file (verified torrents).</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>After some deliberation i have come up with an approach which is better imo:<br /><br /><br />a) there is no need for any PKI, it's not practical. You can just trust the public key directly which you obtain from some website or as part of a magnet link<br />b) there is no need to embed anything in the infohash since authentication is an after-the-fact step. In fact, some author might even endorse torrents that are not created by him later on and add them to his pool of content<br />c) the most common usage scenario are feeds of content out of a single hand such as RSS feeds.<br /><br /><br />To authenticate a torrent you need 3 things:<br /><br />infohash, public key, signature.<br /><br />The info hash is obvious, you have that already... the public key you either already have in your trusted-source list or you can obtain it along with the torrent. The signature can be added to the .torrent or the magnet link.<br /><br /><br />Using Curve25519 public keys and signatures and base32 encoding in the case of magnet links you could assemble something like this:<br /><br />a) just the magnet link, authentication would have to be obtained through an external mechanism<br />magnet:?xt=urn:btih:RQEUWHLWEE325HYQSVG723R6R6KAV7C7<br /><br />b) magnet link with public key and signature. everything you need is there<br />magnet:?xt=urn:btih:RQEUWHLWEE325HYQSVG723R6R6KAV7C7&amp;mt=urn:btpub:GEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQGEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQGEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQGEZA&amp;xt=urn:btsig:GIZTINJWG44DSMBRGIZTINJWG44DSMBRGIZTINJWG44DSMBRGIZQ<br /><br />c) magnet link with public key. The signature could be obtained from the DHT for example and included in the locally stored torrent afterwards.<br />magnet:?xt=urn:btih:RQEUWHLWEE325HYQSVG723R6R6KAV7C7&amp;mt=urn:btpub:GEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQGEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQGEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQGEZA<br /><br />d) only the public key. This can be used to obtain a feed of all torrents from that author, e.g. via a DHT extension<br />magnet:?mt=urn:btpub:GEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQGEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQGEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQGEZA<br /><br />e) authenticated.torrent. Simply contains the public key and the signature <em>outside</em> the info dictionary. Magnet links can be generated from this file.<br /><br /><br /><br />The simplest scenario (e) can be covered with just some additional verification of the .torrent file. The more complex scenarios such as trusted/authored torrent feeds would required changes to the DHT and to magnet link parsing.<br /><br /><br /><br />I think my point is that there is little to no use in embedding the cryptographic data in the info dictionary just to ensure that it's spread virally. Instead it should be optional data for those who actually want to obtain data from a specific source in the first place. If you want a signed edition of ubuntu you go to their homepage and get a .torrent/magnet link from them. If you have a webcaster releasing new content every week you already have his public key and subscribed to his RSS or, if we ever do it, to his DHT feed.<br /><br /><br />In my opinion authored content feeds have far more real-world relevance than signing individual torrents.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="postsignature"><hr />Az dev</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

